“Density on density nonparametric regression: simulation scheme 3”

Frédéric Ferraty

3/24/2021

Set parameters

grid.size = 200 # number of equidistant points where the PDFs are valued
Grid = seq(-1, 1, length = grid.size) # Grid of 'grid.size' equidistant points over [-1, 1] where the PDFs are valued
nbtrigof = 5 # number of trigonometric functions used for building the model error
sigma = 0.2 # standard deviation of the distribution drawing the coefficients used to build model error
N = 100 # sample size
lower = -1 # lower bound of the support of PDFs (Bayes Hilbert space)
upper = 1 # upper bound of the support of PDFs (Bayes Hilbert space)
nu = 0.5 # standard deviation of the truncated distribution (error-in-variable)
rho = 0.9 # mixing coefficient
T = 300 # parameter used to simulate truncated normal distribution

Remarks:

  • lower values for rho and higher values for nu make the complexity of the regession model higher (and hence more difficult to estimate it)

  • The variability in the model errors is controlled with the parameter sigma (here sigma=0.2): higher values of sigma provide higher values for noise-to-signal ratio (\(nsr\)) and naturally, lower values of sigma provide lower values for \(nsr\).


Generate model errors in Bayes space with trigonometric functions \(\epsilon_1, \epsilon_2, \ldots\)

When generating the model \(f_{t+1} = m(f_t)\oplus \epsilon_t\), a first step is to be able to simulate \(\epsilon_0, \epsilon_1,\ldots\), the probability density functions playing the role of model errors. By using the clr transformation, the density-on-density regression model is equivalent \(\mbox{clr}(f_{t+1}) = \mbox{clr} \circ m(f_t) + \mbox{clr}(\epsilon_t)\). Instead of generating directly the errors \(\epsilon_t\) in the Hilbert Bayes space \(\mathcal{B}^2(I)\), it could be more convenient to simulated functional errors \(\eta_t = \mbox{clr}(\epsilon_t)\) in the corresponding Hilbert space \(\mathcal{L}^2_0(I)\).


Model errors \(\eta_1, \, \eta_2, \, \ldots\) in the corresponding Hilbert space \(\mathcal{L}^2_0(I)\)

According to the properties of the clr transformation and the zero-mean constraint in \(\mathcal{B}^2(I)\) of \(\epsilon_t\) given \(f_t\), the model error \(\eta_t\) has to fulfill two constraints:

  1. \(E(\eta_t|f_t) = 0\),

  2. for all \(u\) in \(I\), \(\displaystyle\int_I \eta_t(u) \, du = 0\).

A way to generate such \(\eta_t\)’s is to use the trigonometric functions \(\phi_1, \phi_2, \ldots\) defined on \(I=[-1,\, 1]\): \(\forall k=1,2\ldots, \ \phi_{2k-1}(u) = \cos(k \pi \, u)\) and \(\phi_{2k}(u) = \sin(k \pi \, u)\). One can remark that the \(\phi_k\)’s integrate to 0 for any nonnull integer \(k\).

For any \(u\) in \([-1, \, 1]\), and any subset \(\mathcal{K}\) of nonull integers, set \[ \eta_t(u) \, = \, \sum_{k\in \mathcal{K}} A_{tk} \, \phi_k(u) \] If \(E(A_{tk}|f_t)=0\), then \(E(\eta_t|f_t)=0\) and the integral property of the Fourier basis elements results in \(\int_{-1}^1\eta_t(u) \, du = 0\).

For instance, one can set \[ \eta_t(u) \, = \, A_{t1} \cos(\pi \, u) + A_{t2} \sin(\pi \, u) + A_{t3} \cos(2 \pi u) + A_{t4} \sin(2 \pi \, u) + A_{t5} \cos(3 \pi \, u) \] where \(A_{tj}\)’s are iid zero-mean rrv.

The next graphic displays such model errors \(\eta_t\) with \(A_{t1}\)’s,…,\(A_{t5}\)’s \(\overset{iid}{\sim}\) \(N(0, \sigma^2)\)

trigof = function(K,gridpoints){
  # K first trigonometric functions
  # output is matrix of dimensions (K*length(gridpoint))
  B = matrix(nrow=K,ncol=length(gridpoints))
  for(kk in 1:K){
    even.true = ((kk %% 2) == 0)
    if(even.true){
      p = kk/2
      B[kk,] = sin(pi*p*gridpoints)
    }else{
      p = (kk+1)/2
      B[kk,] = cos(pi*p*gridpoints)
    }
  }
  return(B)
}
# matrix "TRIGOF" contains trigonometric functions, each of them valued at "Grid" points (row 1 --> trigonometric function 1, row 2 --> trigonometric function 2, ...)
TRIGOF = trigof(nbtrigof, Grid)
# display trigonometric functions
ts.plot(t(TRIGOF), gpars = list(xaxt = "n", xlab = "", col = 1:nrow(TRIGOF), lwd = 2, main = paste0(nbtrigof, " first trigonometric functions")))
values = round(seq(-1, 1, length = 10), digits = 1)
axis(1, at = seq(1, grid.size, length = 10), labels = values)

# "At" zero-mean gaussian rrv
At = matrix(rnorm(nbtrigof * N, mean = 0, sd = sigma), nrow = N)
ETA = At %*% TRIGOF
# display m first $\eta_t$'s
m = 10
ts.plot(t(ETA[1:m, ]), gpars = list(xaxt = "n", xlab = "", col = 1:m, lwd = 2, main = paste0(m, " first model errors in clr space")))
values = round(seq(-1, 1, length = 10), digits = 1)
axis(1, at = seq(1, grid.size, length = 10), labels = values)
abline(h = 0, lwd = 2, lty = 2)


Come back to corresponding model errors \(\epsilon_1, \, \epsilon_2, \, \ldots\) in the Bayes space

Come back to \(\epsilon_t\)’s with the inverse of the clr transformation: \(\epsilon_t = \mbox{clr}^{-1}(\eta_t)\)

library(pracma) # package containing the "trapz" routine
NUMERATOR = exp(ETA)
Denominator = 0
for(jj in 1:N){
  Denominator[jj] = trapz(Grid, NUMERATOR[jj, ])
}
EPSILON = NUMERATOR / Denominator
# display m first $\epsilon_t$'s
m = 10
ymax = max(EPSILON)
ts.plot(t(EPSILON[1:m, ]), gpars = list(xaxt = "n", xlab = "", col = 1:m, lwd = 2, ylim = c(0, ymax), main = paste0(m, " first model errors in Bayes space")))
values = round(seq(-1, 1, length = 10), digits = 1)
axis(1, at = seq(1, grid.size, length = 10), labels = values)
abline(h = 1/2, lwd = 2, lty = 2)


Generate the regression operator \(m(\cdot)\) and time series of PDF’s

Let us define the regression operator \(m: \, \mathcal{B}^2(I) \rightarrow \mathcal{B}^2(I)\) such that \[\displaystyle m(f)(y) \, = \, (1-\rho)^{-1} \left\{ \int_{a}^{b} f(x) \, g\left(\frac{y -\rho \, x}{1 - \rho}\right) \, dx \right\} 1_{[-1,\, 1]}(y)\] with \(f\) and \(g\) two given probability densities in \(\mathcal{B}^2(I)\), \(|\rho|<1\) and where \(a = max(-1, \rho^{-1}(y + \rho - 1))\) and \(b = max(1, \rho^{-1}(y - \rho + 1))\). This regression operator has a nice interpretation in terms of convolution. Suppose that, for any \(|\rho|<1\), \(Z = \rho X + (1-\rho) Y\) with \(X\) and \(Y\) two independant r.r.v. and let \(f_Z\) (resp. \(f_X\)) be the PDF of \(Z\) (resp. \(X\)). Then, we have \(f_Z \, = \, m(f_X)\). The regression operator \(m(.)\) corresponds to the transformation resulting from a convex combination of \(X\) with another r.r.v. \(Y\). Based on this remark, we propose the following scheme for simulating our time series of PDFs in the Hilbert Bayes space: \[ f_{t+1} \, = m(f_t) \oplus \epsilon_t \] where the \(\epsilon_t\)’s are the model errors in Bayes space (built previously):

  1. \(m(f_t)\) represents the PDF of \(X_{t+1} = \rho X_t + (1-\rho) Y_{t+1}\) when \(f_t\) is the PDF of \(X_t\),
  2. \(f_{t+1}\) is the obtained PDF when adding some model error \(\epsilon_t\) to \(m(f_t)\).


Distribution of \(Y_t\)’s

Set \(Y_t \, \sim \, g_t = TN(\mu_t, \nu^2)\) where \(TN(\mu_t, \nu^2)\) is the truncated normal distribution over \([-1, \, 1]\) derived from the normal distribution \(N(\mu_t, \nu^2)\) where, for some constant \(T>0\), \(\mu_t = \cos(2 \, \pi \, t \, / \, T)\)

Compute \(f_1\)

Set \(f_1 \equiv g_1\) where \(g_1 = TN(\mu_1, \nu^2)\) with \(\mu_1 = \cos(2 \, \pi \, / \, T)\)

library(truncnorm)
f1 = dtruncnorm(Grid, a = lower, b = upper, mean = cos(2 * pi / T), sd = nu)
PDF = matrix(0, N, grid.size)
REG = matrix(0, N, grid.size)
PDF[1, ] = f1
REG[1, ] = f1


Compute \(f_2 = m(f_1) \oplus \epsilon_1\)

a = Grid + rho - 1
b = Grid - rho + 1
Lb = pmax(-1, a/rho)
Ub = pmin(1, b/rho)
Arg.v = Grid
Range = Ub - Lb
Boolean = (Range > 0)
m.of.f1 = 0
for(ii in 1:grid.size){
  m.of.f1[ii]=0
  if(Boolean[ii]){
    # select grid points (u_i) between Lb[ii] and Ub[ii]
    Arg.x = Grid[(Grid >= Lb[ii]) & (Grid <= Ub[ii])]
    # compute matrix ARG with ARG(k,i) = (v_j - u_i)/(1 - rho)
    ARG = outer(Arg.v, rho * Arg.x, "-")/(1-rho)
    # compute matrix G with G(j,i) = g[(v_j - u_i)/(1 - rho)]
    G = apply(ARG, 2, dtruncnorm, a = lower, b = upper, mean = cos(4*pi/N), sd = nu)
    f1.at.x = dtruncnorm(Arg.x, a = lower, b = upper, mean = cos(2*pi/N), sd = nu)
    Integrand = t(G) * f1.at.x
    m.of.f1[ii] = trapz(Arg.x, Integrand[, ii])/(1 - rho)
  }
}
REG[2, ] = m.of.f1
Numerator = m.of.f1 * EPSILON[1, ]
PDF[2, ] = Numerator / trapz(Grid, Numerator)

Remarks:

  • REG[2, ] contains \(m(f_1)\) valued at grid points (i.e. without model error)

  • PDF[2, ] contains \(m(f_1) \oplus \epsilon_1\) valued at grid points (i.e. with model error)


Iterate to build the whole time series of densities \(f_1,\, f_2 = m(f_1)\oplus\epsilon_1,\ldots,\, f_N=m(f_{N-1})\oplus\epsilon_{N-1}\)

f.new1 = 0
f.new2 = 0
for(tt in 3:N){
  for(ii in 1:grid.size){
    f.new1[ii]=0
    f.new2[ii]=0
    if(Boolean[ii]){
      # select grid points (x_i) between Lb[ii] and Ub[ii]
      Is.in.range = (Grid >= Lb[ii]) & (Grid <= Ub[ii])
      Arg.x = Grid[Is.in.range]
      # compute matrix ARG with ARG(k,i) = (v_k - rho*x_i)/(1 - rho)
      ARG = outer(Arg.v, rho * Arg.x, "-")/(1-rho)
      # compute matrix G with G(j,i) = g[(v_j - rho*x_i)/(1 - rho)]
      G = apply(ARG, 2, dtruncnorm, a = lower, b = upper, mean = cos(2*pi*tt/T), sd = nu)
      Integrand1 = t(G) * REG[tt-1, Is.in.range]
      Integrand2 = t(G) * PDF[tt-1, Is.in.range]
      # compute m(f) at Grid[ii]
      f.new1[ii] = trapz(Arg.x, Integrand1[, ii])/(1 - rho)
      f.new2[ii] = trapz(Arg.x, Integrand2[, ii])/(1 - rho)
    }
  }
  # compute m(f)+error
  REG[tt, ] = f.new1
  Numerator = f.new2 * EPSILON[tt, ]
  PDF[tt, ] = Numerator / trapz(Grid, Numerator)
}

Remarks:

  • REG[tt, ] contains \(m(f_{tt-1})\) valued at grid points (i.e. without model error)

  • PDF[tt, ] contains \(m(f_{tt-1}) \oplus \epsilon_{tt-1}\) valued at grid points (i.e. with model error)


About variabilities

Assessing variability in model errors \(\epsilon_1,\ldots,\epsilon_N\)

Compute \(tr\, \Gamma_{\epsilon,N}\) with \(\Gamma_{\epsilon,N} = N^{-1}\sum_t (\epsilon_t - \overline{\epsilon}) (\epsilon_t - \overline{\epsilon})^T\) \(\Rightarrow\) \(\Gamma_{\epsilon,N} = N^{-1}\sum_t (\epsilon_t - \overline{\epsilon})^T (\epsilon_t - \overline{\epsilon})\)

varepsilon = sum(diag(cov(t(EPSILON))))/N
varepsilon
## [1] 0.02695744


Assessing variability in \(f_1,\ldots,f_N\) with model error (PDFs containing in matrix PDF)

Compute \(tr\, \Gamma_{f_t,N}\) with \(\Gamma_{f_t,N} = N^{-1}\sum_t (f_t - \overline{f}) (f_t - \overline{f})^T\) \(\Rightarrow\) \(tr\, \Gamma_{f_t,N} = N^{-1}\sum_t (f_t - \overline{f})^T (f_t - \overline{f})\)

varf = sum(diag(cov(t(PDF))))/N
varf
## [1] 1.283937


Assessing variability in \(m(f_1),\ldots,m(f_{N-1})\) without model error (PDFs containing in matrix REG)

Compute \(tr\, \Gamma_{m(f_t),N}\) with \(\Gamma_{m(f_t),N} = N^{-1}\sum_t (m(f_t) - \overline{m(f)}) (m(f_t) - \overline{m(f)})^T\) \(\Rightarrow\) \(tr\, \Gamma_{m(f_t),N} = N^{-1}\sum_t (m(f_t) - \overline{m(f)})^T (m(f_t) - \overline{m(f)})\)

varreg = sum(diag(cov(t(REG))))/N
varreg
## [1] 0.05340837


Assessing noise-to-signal ratio

nsr = varepsilon / varreg
nsr
## [1] 0.5047419

Remark: The principle to compute \(nsr\) is the same than in the usual regression setting \(Y = m(X) + \varepsilon\) where, by definition, \(nsr = var(\varepsilon)/var(m(X))\). In the setting of time series of PDFs, one can use an analogous way to compute \(nsr\). In this example, \(nsr \simeq 10\)%. The variability in the model errors is controlled with the parameter sigma (here sigma=0.2): higher values of sigma provide higher values for \(nsr\) (lower values of sigma provide lower values for \(nsr\)).



Display simulated time series of PDFs with a 3D plot

library(colorRamps)
### create a N-colorpalette with "colorRampPalette" R function from "cold" to "warm"
colfunc = colorRampPalette(c("orange", "springgreen", "royalblue", "black"))
#plot(rep(1, N), col=(colfunc(100)), pch = 19, cex = 2)
Colors = colfunc(N)
library(rgl)
plot3d(cbind(Grid, rep(1, grid.size), PDF[1, ]), ylim = c(0, N + 1), type = "l", col = Colors[1], lwd = 3)
for(tt in 2:N){
  plot3d(cbind(Grid, rep(tt, grid.size), PDF[tt, ]), add = TRUE, type = "l", col = Colors[tt], lwd = 3)
}
grid3d(c("x", "y+", "z"))
aspect3d(1, 1, 1)
rglwidget()

Remark: of course, any change on the parameters at the beginning will provide different time series of PDFs.
